<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Lamarckism&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">External links</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.textbookleague.org/54marck.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.textbookleague.org/54marck.htm" rel="nofollow">Nonsense in Schoolbooks - The Imaginary Lamarck</a>:<a href="/wiki/Michael_T._Ghiselin" title="Michael T. Ghiselin" class="mw-redirect">Michael T. Ghiselin</a> recounts Lamarck's times and writings.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.lamarck.cnrs.fr/?lang=en" class="external text" title="http://www.lamarck.cnrs.fr/?lang=en" rel="nofollow">Jean-Baptiste Lamarck&#160;: works and heritage</a>: an English/French web site edited by Pietro Corsi (Oxford Univ.) and realised by CNRS (France - IT team of CRHST). This web site contents all books, texts, manuscripts and the lamarck's herbarium.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.newsweek.com/id/180103/output/print" class="external text" title="http://www.newsweek.com/id/180103/output/print" rel="nofollow">The Sins of the Fathers, Take 2</a>: "At tributes to Darwin, Lamarckism — inheritance of acquired traits — will be the skunk at the party." By Sharon Begley, Newsweek. From the magazine issue dated Jan 26, 2009.</li>
</ul>
